project aim: I perform a statistical analysis for understanding the effect of the environmental temperature on the exponential growth rate of the cases infected by COVID-19 for Belgium and Luxembourg regions.

Hypothesis: \(H_0\beta_1 =0 H1:\beta _1 \neq0\)

Linear Model fit

statistic mode \[ \pmb{Y= \beta_0+\beta_1X+\epsilon \quad where \quad \epsilon \sim N(0,\sigma^2)} \] \[ Y \sim N(0,\sigma^2)\] \[\pmb{E}(y_i)=E(\beta_0+\beta_1x_i+\epsilon_i)=\beta_0+\beta_1x_i+E(\epsilon_i)=\beta_0+\beta_1x_i\]

\[Var(y_i)=Var(\beta_0+\beta_1X+\epsilon_i)=Var(\epsilon_i)=\sigma^2\] ## standard model for the evolution of the infected cases by viruses \[dN/dt=L(N) \cdot F(N), \quad with \quad L(N) = \lambda \cdot N, F(N)=1-N^b\] ##where N(t) is the number of total infected cases,Nmax is the maximum possible number of infected cases.

LUX_fit <- LUX %>% 
  filter(date<end_date & date>start_date) %>%
  filter(weekly_temp>0) %>% 
  lm(logC ~ weekly_temp, data = .)

Fitting model for the data in Luxembourg = 7.96 - 0.105T

\[\hat{Y}=7.96 - 0.105T\] ## Fitting model for the data in Blegium = = 10.9 - 0.107T

\[\hat{Y}= = 10.9 - 0.107T\] ## estimation analysis Hypothesis: \[H_0\beta_1 =0 H1:\beta _1 \neq0\]

##Test based on the hyperthesis

autoplot(LUX_fit)

autoplot(BLG_fit)

## calculate T and P values. As observed from the above results, calculated P value is less than alpha. This gave us enough evidence with 95% confidence we say that we reject null hypothesis. In other words, with %95 confidence beta value is not zero. So we reject $ H_0_1 =0 $.

Residual analysis

Hypothesis: \[H_0: Residual\sim N(0,\sigma^2) H1:Residual \quad !\sim N(0,\sigma^2)\]

library(broom)
BLG_temp_case <- BLG %>% 
  filter(date<end_date & date>start_date) %>%
  filter(weekly_temp>0 ,new_cases>0) %>% 
  mutate(expected = augment(BLG_fit)$.fitted) %>% 
  mutate(residual = log(new_cases)-expected) 


ggplot(BLG_temp_case, aes(x=residual)) + 
    geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..),    
                   binwidth=.5,
                   colour="black", fill="light blue") +
    geom_density(alpha=.2, fill="blue")+
    stat_function(
    fun = dnorm,
    args = list(mean = mean(BLG_temp_case$residual), sd = sd(BLG_temp_case$residual)),
    linetype=2,
    size= 1.5,
    colour="red" )+
  labs(
    x = "Residual", y = "Density",
    title = "Residual distribution of fitting data in Blegium"
  )

## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  y2.res
## W = 0.99044, p-value = 0.8603

Test result

The selected significance level alpha = 0.05 which is less than p value for both cases. This means, p value area coves the alpha completely so we dont have enough evidence to reject null hypothesis. Hence the residual population is Normal.

      col = expression(paste('Values of ', mu)))+ 
    annotate("text", x=-0.15, y=10, colour="darkblue", label= expression(paste("Belgium", hat(beta)[1]))) +
    annotate("text", x=-0.08, y=22,colour="darkred", label= expression(paste("Luxembourg", hat(beta)[1])))
